f their critical position. She demonstrates how this first generation of modern Chinese literary critics practiced criticism, examining the skills and arguments they used to negotiate their institutional and ideological relations with state-party power. This exceptional case of intellectual engagement offers broader insight on critical literature's humanistic aims and methods in the context of intellectual globalization and changing political climates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Chinesey20th century. 0aCriticismxPolitical aspectszChina. 0aCriticismzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847955240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479552423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479552/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles